  "prompt": "Why is a single covalent bond formed even if the valence electrons repel each other?",
  "response": "A single covalent bond is formed despite the initial repulsion of valence electrons due to several key factors:\n\n1. Electrostatic attraction\n- Electrons are attracted to the positively charged nucleus of each atom\n- Attractive forces between electrons and nuclei overcome initial electron repulsion\n\n2. Energy minimization\n- Atoms seek a lower energy state when forming a bond\n- Sharing electrons reduces the overall potential energy of the system\n- The net attractive forces outweigh the initial electron repulsion\n\n3. Orbital overlap\n- Valence electrons from different atoms share and overlap their orbitals\n- This overlap creates a region of electron density between nuclei\n- The shared electrons are attracted to both atomic nuclei simultaneously\n\n4. Quantum mechanical principles\n- Electron wave functions interact and merge\n- Quantum tunneling allows electrons to occupy a shared space\n- Probability of electron distribution changes during bond formation\n\n5. Reduced electron-electron repulsion\n- Shared electrons are distributed between two nuclei\n- This distribution reduces the effective repulsive force\n- The electrons experience a more stable configuration\n\nThese mechanisms work together to enable covalent bond formation, demonstrating that the attractive forces ultimately overcome initial electron repulsion.",
